# Docs Pattern

## File types

- Use `.mdx` for all walkthrough pages (required for component imports).
- Use `.md` only for simple content with no components.
- The introduction page (`src/content/docs/index.mdx`) uses `template: splash`.

## Frontmatter template

Every walkthrough page must start with:

```mdx
---
title: <Page Title>
description: <One sentence describing what this page covers.>
draft: true        # Remove only when the page is ready to publish
sidebar:
  label: <Short label shown in the sidebar>
---
```

Remove `draft: true` when the page is ready to go live. Draft pages are excluded from production builds (`npm run build`) but visible in dev (`npm run dev`).

## MDX imports

Always import components at the top of the file, after the frontmatter:

```mdx
import { Steps, Aside, Tabs, TabItem, FileTree, Badge, Card, CardGrid, LinkCard, LinkButton } from '@astrojs/starlight/components';
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import Checklist from '@/components/Checklist.astro';
import Tooltip from '@/components/Tooltip.astro';
```

Only import what you actually use on that page.

## Page structure for walkthrough pages

Follow this order:

1. **External repo Aside** — if the page uses Terraform or GitOps resources
2. **Checklist** — progress tracker at the top
3. **Overview** heading — plain text intro with Tooltip terms
4. **Repository layout** — FileTree showing relevant files
5. **Steps** — the actual procedure

```mdx
<Aside type="note">
  Terraform code: [aws-eks-terraform](https://github.com/jajera/aws-eks-terraform).
  Resources for this section live under `modules/<section>/`.
</Aside>

<Checklist id="<section>-<page>" items={['Step 1', 'Step 2']} />

## Overview

Text with <Tooltip term="vpc" /> inline terms.

## Repository layout

<FileTree>
- modules/
  - <section>/
    - **main.tf**
</FileTree>

## Steps

<Steps>
1. Step one. <Badge text="Required" variant="tip" size="small" />
   ...
</Steps>
```

## MDX: JSX inside list items (e.g. inside `<Steps>`) — critical

**This is the most common MDX bug in this repo.** Block-level JSX (`<Tabs>`, `<Aside>`, etc.) inside a step **must** be indented so the parser treats it as part of the list item. Wrong indentation causes: `Expected a closing tag for '<Tabs>' before the end of 'listItem'`.

**Rule:** Indent the **entire** JSX block as list-item content. Use these levels consistently:

| Level | Indentation | What |
| ----- | ----------- | ---- |
| Step content (code, text, `<Tabs>`) | **3 spaces** | Same as the step’s body |
| Inside `<Tabs>`: `<TabItem>`, `</TabItem>` | **5 spaces** | 3 + 2 |
| Inside `<TabItem>`: code blocks, etc. | **6 spaces** | 3 + 3 |

**Correct** — `<Tabs>` and every line inside it indented as continuation of the list item:

```mdx
<Steps>
4. **Apply and update kubeconfig.**

   ```bash frame="terminal"
   terraform apply
   ```

   Then update your local kubeconfig:

   <Tabs syncKey="tool">
     <TabItem label="AWS CLI">
      ```bash frame="terminal"
      aws eks update-kubeconfig ...
      ```
     </TabItem>
     <TabItem label="Terraform output">
      ...
     </TabItem>
   </Tabs>

5. **Verify.**
   ...
</Steps>
```

**Wrong** — `<TabItem>` or inner content at less indentation (e.g. 2 spaces) so the parser thinks the list item ended before `</Tabs>`:

```mdx
   <Tabs syncKey="tool">
  <TabItem label="AWS CLI">   <!-- BAD: 2 spaces ends the list item in parser’s view -->
```

When creating or editing walkthrough pages, **always** indent any `<Tabs>`, `<Aside>`, or other block JSX that appears inside a numbered step. If you see `Expected a closing tag for '<Tabs>' before the end of 'listItem'`, fix indentation: 3 spaces for step content, 5 for `<TabItem>`, 6 for content inside a tab.

## Checklist usage

- `id` must be unique across the entire site. Use the pattern `<section>-<page>` (e.g. `networking-vpc`).
- `items` should mirror the key outcomes of the page, not individual sub-steps.
- Checklist state is saved in `localStorage` and persists across visits.

## Tooltip usage

- Use `<Tooltip term="vpc" />` for AWS/Kubernetes abbreviations and jargon.
- Terms are defined in `src/data/glossary.ts`. Add new terms there — do not inline definitions in page content.
- Use the `term` key in lowercase (e.g. `term="nat"`, `term="iam"`).
- You can override the display text with the slot: `<Tooltip term="vpc">Virtual Private Cloud</Tooltip>`.

## Images

- Store images under `src/assets/<section>/` (e.g. `src/assets/networking/vpc-diagram.png`).
- Name files: lowercase, hyphenated, descriptive (e.g. `vpc-diagram.png`, `node-group-overview.png`).
- Reference with the `@/` alias and the `<Image>` component:

```mdx
import vpcDiagram from '@/assets/networking/vpc-diagram.png';
<Image src={vpcDiagram} alt="VPC architecture showing public and private subnets" />
```

## Expressive Code conventions

Apply to all fenced code blocks:

- Always add `title="filename.ext"` to code blocks that show file content.
- Use `frame="terminal"` for shell commands (or `bash`/`sh` which auto-detects).
- Use ` ```diff lang="hcl" ` for before/after Terraform changes.
- Use `{line}` or `{start-end}` to highlight important lines.

## External repo references

When a page uses Terraform infrastructure code, open with:

```mdx
<Aside type="note">
  Terraform code: [aws-eks-terraform](https://github.com/jajera/aws-eks-terraform).
  Resources for this section live under `modules/<section>/`.
</Aside>
```

When a page uses ArgoCD/GitOps manifests, reference:

```mdx
<Aside type="note">
  Platform manifests live in [aws-eks-platform](https://github.com/jajera/aws-eks-platform).
</Aside>
```

## Sidebar order

**Never number file names.** Sidebar order is controlled entirely in `astro.config.mjs`.

### Draft workflow — critical

Starlight throws a build error if a sidebar `slug` references a page that is `draft: true`, because draft pages are excluded from production builds. The rule is:

- **Do NOT add a page to the sidebar until it is published (draft removed).**
- Pre-created draft pages live in the file system and are visible in `npm run dev`, but are not listed in the sidebar config until ready.

### Publishing a page

1. Create the `.mdx` file with `draft: true` (already done for all sections).
2. Write the content.
3. When ready to publish: remove `draft: true` from the frontmatter.
4. Uncomment or add the `slug` entry in the correct `items` array in `astro.config.mjs`.
5. If the section group didn't exist in the sidebar yet, add the whole group block (example below).

```js
// astro.config.mjs — add when Foundations batch is ready
{
  label: 'Foundations',
  collapsed: false,
  badge: { text: 'Start here', variant: 'tip' },
  items: [
    { slug: 'foundations' },
    { slug: 'foundations/prerequisites' },
  ],
},
```

Template groups for all batches are already commented out in `astro.config.mjs` — just uncomment when ready.

## Internal links and base path

The site is built with `base: '/aws-eks-walkthrough'` (see `astro.config.mjs`). All internal links to doc pages **must** include this base path so they work when deployed (e.g. at `https://jajera.github.io/aws-eks-walkthrough/`).

- **Correct:** `[AWS Account](/aws-eks-walkthrough/foundations/prerequisites/aws-account/)`
- **Wrong:** `[AWS Account](/foundations/prerequisites/aws-account/)` (missing base; will break in production)

The `/aws-eks-walkthrough/` segment is **not** a duplicate; it is the required base path. Do not remove it from links or hrefs.

## Theory-first pattern

Some batches have non-trivial theory that is best separated from the build steps. The Networking batch follows this pattern:

- **Concepts page** (`networking/concepts.mdx`) — theory only; no Terraform, no steps. Covers VPC basics, subnets, AZs, VPC CNI, security groups, endpoint access modes, and what EKS needs from the network.
- **Build page** (`networking/vpc.mdx`) — hands-on Terraform steps; short Overview that links to the Concepts page for "why."

**When to use it:** apply the theory-first pattern when a batch has enough background knowledge (networking primitives, IAM concepts, certificate theory, etc.) that it would clutter the build page. Create a `concepts.mdx` in the batch folder and link to it from the index LinkCard and from the build page's intro.

**Sidebar order:** Concepts always comes before the build page — `{ slug: 'batch/concepts' }` then `{ slug: 'batch/build' }`.

## Default AWS region

Always use `ap-southeast-6` (AWS Asia Pacific — New Zealand) as the example region in all docs, code blocks, config snippets, and CLI commands. Do not substitute other regions such as `us-east-1` or `ap-southeast-1` unless the user explicitly requests a different region.

Examples:

```bash frame="terminal"
aws configure set region ap-southeast-6
export AWS_REGION=ap-southeast-6
aws eks update-kubeconfig --region ap-southeast-6 --name <cluster-name>
```

